# Rhomboids

> The rhomboids (**major** and **minor**) are deep back muscles connecting the vertebral column to the medial border of the [[Scapula]]. They **retract and elevate** the scapula, working in opposition to [[Serratus Anterior]].

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Muscular System]]
- Related: [[Scapula]], [[Trapezius]], [[Serratus Anterior]]
- Nerve: **Dorsal scapular nerve (C4, C5)**
- Blood supply: Dorsal scapular artery

## 🔬 Details

| Muscle | Origin | Insertion | Action |
|--------|--------|-----------|--------|
| **Rhomboid minor** | Nuchal ligament (C7–T1 spinous processes) | Medial border of scapula (at level of spine) | Retract scapula; elevate medial border |
| **Rhomboid major** | T2–T5 spinous processes | Medial border of scapula (below spine) | Retract scapula; downward rotation of glenoid |
| Both | — | — | Hold scapula against thoracic wall |

**Nerve:** Dorsal scapular nerve (C4–C5)

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Rhomboid strain** — interscapular pain; common in desk workers / poor posture (rounded shoulders → stretched rhomboids)
- **Dorsal scapular nerve injury** — winged scapula (medial winging); less pronounced than serratus anterior palsy
- **Postural imbalance** — weak rhomboids + tight pectorals → protracted scapula, kyphosis

